  "text": "The oxygen oxidation reaction without a copper catalyst also produced 2,6-dimethoxy-1,4-benzoquinone, which is not present in the reaction with a copper catalyst (Fig. 3 and 4) . The identification of this peak was based on its mass spectrum which clearly showed a different spectral pattern from vanillic acid even though its retention time is very close to that of vanillic acid. The formation of this compound is attributed to the hydroperoxyl radical (produced from oxygen reactions with organic substances) reacting at the 4-position of the lignin (Stenius, 2000; Sarkanen and Ludwig, 1971; [CITATION_1] . The absence of this compound in the product mixture of the copper catalysed oxygen oxidation reaction suggests that the hydroperoxyl radical does not play an important role in the copper catalysed oxidation reaction. This then suggests that the oxygen oxidation reactions with a copper catalyst are caused by the catalyst since the lignin is oxidised by the copper catalyst rather than by oxygen radicals.",
